'''Shōshoi''' (少初位), also known as '''Oshisaka no Hikohito no Ōe no Miko''' (押坂彦人大兄皇子, [[生没年不詳]]), was a member of the imperial family during the [[Asuka period]]. He was also referred to as '''Oshisaka no Hikohito Prince''', '''Maroko Prince''', '''Taishi Hikohito Prince''', '''Oshisaka Hikohito Taishi''', and '''Ōso Taishi'''. He was the first son of '''{{ill|Emperor Bidatsu|ja|敏達天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}''' and his consort, {{ill|Hirohime|ja|広姫|12=draft|12=draft}}. His children include '''{{ill|Emperor Jomei|ja|舒明天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}''' and {{ill|Prince Chinu|ja|茅渟王|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The modern {{ill|Imperial House of Japan|ja|皇室|12=draft|12=draft}} is descended in the male line from Shōshoi.
== Life == Born as the first son of {{ill|Emperor Bidatsu|ja|敏達天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, his mother was {{ill|Hirohime|ja|広姫|12=draft|12=draft}}, daughter of {{ill|Prince Okinaga Makoto|ja|息長真手王|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Shōshoi was a prominent figure of the Bidatsu lineage, which was unconnected to the Soga clan. He maintained independent financial bases such as the {{ill|Oshisaka|ja|忍坂部|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Maroko|ja|丸子部|12=draft|12=draft}} estates and resided outside the royal capital at the Mimata Palace (水派宮), likely located in {{ill|Kōryō, Nara|ja|奈良県河合町|12=draft|12=draft}}. After the death of {{ill|Emperor Yōmei|ja|用明天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} in [[587]], he was considered a potential heir to the throne. However, the rise of the Soga clan resulted in his disappearance from historical records. Some speculate he was {{ill|assassinated|ja|暗殺|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>Speculations include assassination during the [[587]] conflict between the Soga and Mononobe clans ({{ill|Yukihisa Yamano|ja|山尾幸久|12=draft|12=draft}}) or an accidental death ({{ill|Hajime Wada|ja|和田萃|12=draft|12=draft}}), but there is no historical evidence.</ref>. Nevertheless, based on records in the ''{{ill|Ichidai Yōki|ja|一代要記|12=draft|12=draft}}'' and ''{{ill|Shōunroku|ja|紹運録|12=draft|12=draft}}'', and the birth year of {{ill|Emperor Jomei|ja|舒明天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} (593), it is believed Shōshoi survived until after [[592]], during the reign of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}.
His private estates, including those inherited by his son Emperor Jomei, provided significant financial support for non-Soga claimants to the throne. These estates, called "Imperial Grand Progenitor Named Divisions," were later returned to the state following the {{ill|Taika Reforms|ja|大化の改新|12=draft|12=draft}} (645).
== Genealogy == Based on the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}}'': * Consort: {{ill|Ohari Princess|ja|小墾田皇女|12=draft|12=draft}}, daughter of Emperor Bidatsu and Empress Suiko * Consort: {{ill|Sakurai Yumihari Princess|ja|桜井弓張皇女|12=draft|12=draft}} ''' Children: Prince Yamashiro, Prince Kasanu * Consort: {{ill|Nukatehime Princess|ja|糠手姫皇女|12=draft|12=draft}} ''' Children: {{ill|Emperor Jomei|ja|田村王|12=draft|12=draft}}, Prince Nakatsu, {{ill|Prince Tara|ja|多良王|12=draft|12=draft}} * Consort: {{ill|Ōmata Princess|ja|大俣女王|12=draft|12=draft}}, sister of {{ill|Prince Kan|ja|漢王|12=draft|12=draft}} ''' Children: {{ill|Prince Chinu|ja|茅渟王|12=draft|12=draft}}, Princess Kuwata
=== Descendants === Shōshoi's descendants, including Emperor Jomei, played pivotal roles in the continuation of the non-Soga lineage during the Asuka period.
== References == <references /> == See Also == * {{ill|Oshisaka no Hikohito's Retainers|ja|押坂部毛屎|12=draft|12=draft}}
